				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I realize this isn't the best place for this suggestion, but if anybody thinks this might be a good idea, and knows where it should go, please pass it on.
<br />

<br />
I figured maybe implementing something along the lines of if you have 5 or more NPC's chasing after one person, like they all had just one person on top of their hate list, and these NPC's were also within X proximity of each other (in a multi-kite situation), if both of those things are true, give one of the NPC's the ability to summon just that one player that's on top of their hate list.  This would limit the bards kiting abilities to 4, like Druids and Wizards quad-kite etc.  Or you could bump it up to 5 or 6, but keep it much lower than 10+ etc. which borderlines abuse, etc.
<br />

<br />
Also, have this only work if the NPC's are within X levels of the PC's level.  So you don't have level 20 bears or something summoning lvl 65 bards.  But you would have lvl 57 Hobgoblins in PoN summoning lvl 60 bards if they had like 15 chasing them, etc.  Also perhaps make the NPC's need to have a certain % of the dmg done by that PC, or just at a certain health level as well.
<br />

<br />
So basically, 6-10+ NPC's all having one person on the top of their hate list, and not stationary, taking damage from that PC, and within a certain # of levels below, or anything even or above to that PC being able to summon that PC if the NPC's are within close proximity to each other (in kite formation).
<br />

<br />
So it'd be like this -
<br />
PC is at top of NPC's hate list - check
<br />
PC is at top of 6+ NPC's hate list - check
<br />
NPC is within X units from these other NPC's - check
<br />
NPC is not stationary - check
<br />
NPC's are damaged past 95% or whatever - check
<br />

<br />
This seems like a good fix, and would directly address multi-kiting, and not really mess up anything else, at least that I can think of.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
